Insights_ClaimsAuthorization_ReadDisclos:
{"auth_Text":"Do You authorize the disclosure of PHI to Voya pursuant to the terms of this Authorization?","disclosure_parts":[{"disclosure_title":"Authorization to Disclose Protected Health Information","disclosure_description_1":"By signing this authorization (\"Authorization\"), you (\"You\" or \"Patient\") authorize any health plan, healthcare clearinghouse, physician, health care professional, hospital, clinic, laboratory, pharmacy, pharmacy benefits manager, medical facility, other health care provider that has provided health care treatment or services to You or on Your behalf within the past one year, and any and all other medical sources, (\"Providers\") unless otherwise provided by state law, to disclose certain protected health information (\"PHI\") maintained by the Provider concerning You to Voya Benefits Company, LLC and its agents, employees, representatives, and affiliates (collectively, the \"Voya\"). The purpose for disclosure of this PHI is for the Voya to use your health claims data to provide You with the full scope of myVoyage services, including managing your benefit options, health care spend, and/or reminders for preventative care.","disclosure_description_2":""},{"disclosure_title":"The PHI authorized to be disclosed to Voya under this Authorization includes:","disclosure_description_1":"
  • Start and end dates of a medical service, treatment, prescription, or event;
  • The name of treating Provider(s);
  • Previous and current plan year summary of group health plan, dental, and vision spend, including breakdown by category and dollar amount;
  • Previous and current plan year summary of medical claims information and utilization; and
  • Medical codes that describe the services, treatment, prescription, and/or diagnosis You received as well as any categories under which you were billed.","disclosure_description_2":""},{"disclosure_title":"By providing this Authorization, You also understand that the above PHI may include information about You concerning:","disclosure_description_1":"
  • Diagnosis or treatment of HIV/AIDS or other sexually transmitted diseases;
  • Diagnosis or treatment of mental illness (excluding psychotherapy notes); or
  • Diagnosis or treatment of substance use disorder, except for information protected by 42 CFR Part 2 information.
    • ","disclosure_description_2":""},{"disclosure_title":"Additional Information","disclosure_description_1":"The provision of treatment, payment, enrollment in a health plan, or eligibility for benefits does not depend on whether You sign this Authorization. Voya will not sell or share your health claims data with any external or unaffiliated third-party. If You decline to provide this Authorization, Voya will not be able to provide the full scope of myVoyage services listed above.","disclosure_description_2":"By signing below, You understand this Authorization shall remain in force for so long as You are actively enrolled in myVoyage. A copy of this Authorization is as valid as the original. Upon receipt of this Authorization, and until its revocation as set forth below, Voya will collect the PHI, and will continue to collect PHI, to perform the services for myVoyage application. You have the right to revoke this Authorization in writing, at any time, either directly through the myVoyage application or by sending a written request for revocation to Voya at 250 Marquette Ave. Suite 900, Minneapolis, MN 55401, Attention: Compliance Officer. Your revocation will be effective upon Voya's receipt. This revocation will not undo the collection or use of Your PHI that already occurred based on this authorization. Any information that is disclosed to Voya pursuant to this Authorization may be re-disclosed if permitted under applicable law, and upon such re disclosure, such information may no longer be protected by federal or state confidentiality laws, including HIPAA. You should retain a copy of this Authorization for Your records. You have a right to receive a copy of this Authorization upon request by writing to: 250 Marquette Ave., Suite 900, Minneapolis, MN 55401, Attention: Compliance Officer."},{"disclosure_title":"By selecting \"Yes\" below, You are electronically signing this Authorization and representing that You have authority to act under HIPAA either on your own behalf as the Patient and/or as a personal representative for an enrollee, including a dependent, covered under your group health plan. Your electronic signature will be legally binding and enforceable and the legal equivalent of your handwritten signature.","disclosure_description_1":"","disclosure_description_2":""}]}

Your doctor knows you and your health history, including what medications you are taking and what chronic conditions might need to be considered in your treatment. Plus, the co-pay for a visit to your doctor’s office will cost far less than a trip to the emergency room."},{"header":"Urgent care/Retail health clinic","body":"If you can’t reach your doctor or need care outside of regular office hours, urgent care centers and retail health clinics are good options. Retail health clinics are walk-in clinics are found in many large pharmacies and retail stores. They are staffed to treat simple conditions, like cold and flu, ear infections and skin conditions. Urgent care centers have physicians on staff and can provide care for a greater range of conditions, including performing x-rays. In most cases, the out-of-pocket cost for visiting a retail health clinic or urgent care center will cost less than a trip to the emergency room, but it’s always a good idea to check to make sure the location you select is covered by your plan."},{"header":"ERs","body":"Emergency rooms are designed to treat urgent, and life-threatening conditions and aren’t the place for routine care or minor ailments. Some networks may be larger than others or may include different choices of providers in your local area. It's important to understand these differences when choosing a plan to meet your specific needs. Also, when you choose a plan, make sure your provider is part of the network associated with that plan."},{"header":"What's the difference between using in-network and out-of-network providers?","body":"To help you save money, most health plans provide access to a network of doctors, facilities, and pharmacies. These doctors and facilities must meet certain credentialing to be part of the network. If a doctor or facility has no contract with your health plan, they're considered out-of-network and can charge you full price. It's usually much higher than the in-network discounted rate."},{"header":"Why does Out-of-Network care cost me more out of pocket?","body":"You're probably paying full price. When health insurers don't have a contracted relationship with out-of-network doctors and facilities, they can't control what is charged for services. If your doctor's bill is higher than what your plan will pay, you might have to pay the difference. Many health plans list an amount that is the most they'll pay for a certain service received out-of-network. If the doctor or facility charges more than your plan is willing to pay, you could be responsible for paying the difference in addition to your deductible, copay, and/or coinsurance. In-network doctors and facilities have agreed not to charge you more than the agreed-upon cost."},{"header":"What’s the cost for In-Network vs.Out-of-Network?","body":"Out-of-network costs can add up quickly, even for routine care.
